nity and its non-living environment, are obtained not only by simple inductive and deductive inference alone but by the iterative inference described in the paper. The author also examines several areas of relative ‘goodness’ which have been postulated as constituting an optimum human environment. The author discusses the conflict of values owing to the many types of goodnesses which have been brought under the ‘ethic’ umbrella. He further discusses the manner in which the cosmic order philosophy of Dooyeweerd not only provides an interlocking scale of goodness in which values of higher or lower orders may be anticipated or viewed in retrospect but also the philosophical structure within which the final decision can be made. Examples are presented to illustrate the way in which philosophy helps the decision-maker by disclosing the significance of the impacts of alternative land uses in an organized way. The roles of life view philosophies in decision making are also introduced. In order to present the planning process as a unified whole, a transdisciplinary model of six levels of formulation has been introduced. The formulation at each level is both a ‘particular’, in relation to the formulation above it, and a ‘situation’ which provides meaning for the particular formulated at the level below. This linkage is provided by differing forms of enquiry which bind the disciplinary levels together at the various interlevels.
